On 4/20/06, jason r tibbetts &lt;tibbettj@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;
&gt; Tiago Fernandez wrote:
&gt; &gt; Ok, I&#39;m still moving to JUnit4, so I&#39;ll show you an example I have with
&gt; &gt; JUnit3:
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;    /**
&gt; &gt;     * Trying to login with username and password
&gt; &gt;     */
&gt; &gt;    public void testLoginValidation() throws Exception {
&gt; &gt;       try {
&gt; &gt;          securityHandler.login(&quot;pt&quot;, &quot;portugiesisch&quot;);
&gt; &gt;          fail(&quot;Username with 2 characters must not be allowed.&quot;);
&gt; &gt;       }
&gt; &gt;       catch (Exception ex) {
&gt; &gt;          // passed :-)
&gt; &gt;       }
&gt; &gt;       try {
&gt; &gt;          securityHandler.login(&quot;deutsch&quot;, &quot;de&quot;);
&gt; &gt;          fail(&quot;Password with 2 characters must not be allowed.&quot;);
&gt; &gt;       }
&gt; &gt;       catch (Exception ex) {
&gt; &gt;          // passed :-)
&gt; &gt;       }
&gt; &gt;       try {
&gt; &gt;          securityHandler.login(&quot;&quot;, &quot;&quot;);
&gt; &gt;          fail(&quot;Blank username and password must not be allowed.&quot;);
&gt; &gt;       }
&gt; &gt;       catch (Exception ex) {
&gt; &gt;          // passed :-)
&gt; &gt;       }
&gt; &gt;    }
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Please let me know if it&#39;s enough.
&gt;
&gt; Look at your application&#39;s requirements to determine whether it&#39;s
&gt; enough. I can think of many, many more tests that you may want to do:
&gt;
&gt; * username or password with 1 character
&gt; * separate tests for blank password and blank username (otherwise, how
&gt; do you know which one triggered the exception?)
&gt; * more specific exception handling
&gt; * null arguments
&gt; * validating that a successful login actually /does/ something (i.e. try
&gt; accessing a resources that required being logged in)
&gt; * etc.
&gt;
&gt; I also recommend putting each one of these try/catch blocks in its own
&gt; test method. This will make it much easier to debug failed tests and to
&gt; understand what&#39;s being tested.
&gt;


